            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is an HTML entity encoder?</h2>
              <p>
                An HTML entity encoder converts characters that have special
                meaning in HTML into their safe <em>entity</em> equivalents. For
                example:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box mono text-sm">
                <div>
                  <span class="font-semibold">Raw:</span> &lt;div
                  class="note"&gt;5 &lt; 10 &amp; 10 &gt; 5&lt;/div&gt;
                </div>
                <div>
                  <span class="font-semibold">Encoded:</span> &amp;lt;div
                  class=&amp;quot;note&amp;quot;&amp;gt;5 &amp;lt; 10 &amp;amp;
                  10 &amp;gt; 5&amp;lt;/div&amp;gt;
                </div>
              </div>
              <p>
                Browsers interpret characters like <code>&lt;</code>,
                <code>&gt;</code>, and <code>&amp;</code> as part of HTML tags
                or entities. Encoding them ensures they are displayed as literal
                text instead of being executed as markup.
              </p>

              <h2>When should you encode HTML entities?</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>Displaying user-generated content inside a web page.</li>
                <li>Showing code snippets in documentation or blog posts.</li>
                <li>
                  Embedding HTML inside templates, JSON, or JavaScript strings.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Preventing cross-site scripting (XSS) and layout breakage.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Minimal vs non-ASCII vs full encoding</h3>
              <p>
                <strong>Minimal encoding</strong> is usually enough for HTML
                safety:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><code>&amp;</code> → <code>&amp;amp;</code></li>
                <li><code>&lt;</code> → <code>&amp;lt;</code></li>
                <li><code>&gt;</code> → <code>&amp;gt;</code></li>
                <li><code>"</code> → <code>&amp;quot;</code></li>
                <li>
                  <code>'</code> → <code>&amp;#39;</code> (or
                  <code>&amp;apos;</code> in XML)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                <strong>Non-ASCII encoding</strong> additionally encodes
                characters above U+007F (like emoji or accented letters), which
                can be useful for legacy systems or email templates.
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong>Full encoding</strong> converts every character to an
                entity. This is rarely needed but can be handy when embedding
                arbitrary text in contexts with strict escaping rules.
              </p>

              <h2>Named vs decimal vs hex entities</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Named entities</strong> – human-readable, e.g.
                  <code>&amp;copy;</code>, <code>&amp;nbsp;</code>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Decimal entities</strong> – use Unicode code point in
                  base 10, e.g. <code>&amp;#169;</code>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Hex entities</strong> – use base 16, e.g.
                  <code>&amp;#xA9;</code>.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Browsers understand all three forms. Not every character has a
                named entity, so this tool will fall back to decimal or hex when
                needed.
              </p>

              <h2>Examples</h2>
              <div class="formula-box mono text-sm">
                <div>
                  <span class="font-semibold">Input:</span> 5 &lt; 10 &amp; 10
                  &gt; 5
                </div>
                <div>
                  <span class="font-semibold">Encoded (named):</span> 5 &amp;lt;
                  10 &amp;amp; 10 &amp;gt; 5
                </div>
                <div>
                  <span class="font-semibold">Encoded (decimal):</span> 5
                  &amp;#60; 10 &amp;#38; 10 &amp;#62; 5
                </div>
                <div>
                  <span class="font-semibold">Encoded (hex):</span> 5 &amp;#x3C;
                  10 &amp;#x26; 10 &amp;#x3E; 5
                </div>
              </div>

              <h2>Security note</h2>
              <p>
                This HTML entity encoder/decoder runs entirely in your browser
                using JavaScript. No data is sent to a server. Still, avoid
                pasting highly sensitive information into any online tool unless
                absolutely necessary.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>Does this tool support emoji and non‑Latin scripts?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Emoji, CJK characters, and other Unicode symbols can be
                encoded to decimal or hex entities and decoded back.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use it for XML or XHTML?</h3>
              <p>
                The core entities (<code>&amp;</code>, <code>&lt;</code>,
                <code>&gt;</code>, quotes) are compatible with XML/XHTML. For
                strict XML, prefer <code>&amp;#39;</code> over
                <code>&amp;apos;</code> for maximum compatibility with old HTML
                parsers.
              </p>
